Introduction

What’s all this for?

The New York Metropolitan area has a problem.

New Jersey Transit (NJT), the third largest public transportation system in the United States, operates a fleet of ~1,200 active trains every day, accounting for early 300 million rides annually across more than 5,000 square miles serviced area. Featuring rail stations across three states, commuters from across the Northeast rely on the transit network to get to work, school, and other daily activities safely, quickly, and reliably.

Despite the important role the NJT plays in the lives of its commuters, there is currently no publicly-available system to accurately predict potential train delays in any of the station lines. This presents a big problem for commuters, as delayed trains drastically affect one’s ability to perform daily tasks and arrive to scheduled meetings on time. Having an accessing which trains are likely to be late puts the power back in the hands of the commuters, who are often left behind in the event of train malfunction. This report aims to suggest one solution to this issue.

The Northeast Corridor is a particularly interesting transit line within the NJT system, as it is shares rail space with Amtrak service and is by far the busiest line. Due to these factors, we have decided to focus our evaluation to study this line.

Data and Methodology

The following analysis utilizes linear regression, cross validation, and ______ analyses to predict the number of minutes late a train will be, given its station of origin, time of departure, and ________.

Data is pulled from the following link: [https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/pranavbadami/nj-transit-amtrak-nec-performance?select=2018_11.csv] The dataset reports on train delay minutes for the entirety of the NJ Transit rail system, as well as selected Amtrak lines, from March 2018 to May 2020.

  rename(To.Tract = GEOID)  %>%
  mutate(to_lng = unlist(map(geometry, 1)),
         to_lat = unlist(map(geometry, 2)))%>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  select(-geometry)%>%
  na.omit

Evaluating Weather Patterns

To have a better understanding of the potential impact that weather patterns have on train performance, weather data is observed for the NYC weather station from the year 2019. Pulling in information such as temperature, precipitation, wind speed, and overall visibility allows for fluctuations in train driving conditions, as well as may help explain delays caused by inclement weather such as snow and particularly bad storms.

The following graphs highlight an example of the weather conditions later explored in the model: Precipitation, Wind Speed, Temperature, and Visibility.

weather.Data <- 
  riem_measures(station = "WRI", date_start = "2019-01-01", date_end = "2019-01-31")
weather.Panel  <-  
  weather.Data %>%
  dplyr::select(valid, tmpf, p01i, sknt, vsby)%>%
  replace(is.na(.), 0) %>%
    mutate(interval60 = ymd_h(substr(valid,1,13))) %>%
    mutate(week = week(interval60),
           dotw = wday(interval60, label=TRUE)) %>%
    group_by(interval60) %>%
    summarize(Temperature = max(tmpf),
              Precipitation = sum(p01i),
              Wind_Speed = max(sknt),
              Visibility = max(vsby)) %>%
    mutate(Temperature = ifelse(Temperature == 0, 42, Temperature))
grid.arrange( ncol=2,

Further Data Cleaning + Lagged Variables

Further data cleaning is needed in order to render the information useful to building out the model. First, we join the weather data to the appropriate stations as seen across the three states.

Next, holidays and special events are added to the analysis. This is particularly important, as different holidays throughout the year are common sources of rush hour traffic for both car and public transit commuting populations.

Lastly, lagged variables are created from previous delayed minutes along each train route. Analyzing temporally-lagged variables are essential to this study, as understanding the previous delays of a given train will heavily inform the likelihood of the train arriving late to its next station.

time lag variables

trip_panel <- 
  trip_panel %>% 
  arrange( interval60) %>% 
  mutate(lagHour = dplyr::lag(delay_minutes,1),
         lag2Hours = dplyr::lag(delay_minutes,2),
         lag3Hours = dplyr::lag(delay_minutes,3),
         lag4Hours = dplyr::lag(delay_minutes,4),
         lag12Hours = dplyr::lag(delay_minutes,12),
         lag1day = dplyr::lead(delay_minutes,24),
         leadHour = dplyr::lead(delay_minutes,1),
         lead2Hours = dplyr::lead(delay_minutes,2),
         lead3Hours = dplyr::lead(delay_minutes,3),
         lead4Hours = dplyr::lead(delay_minutes,4),
         lead12Hours = dplyr::lead(delay_minutes,12),
         lead1day = dplyr::lead(delay_minutes,24)
        )%>%
  mutate(holidayLag = case_when(dplyr::lag(holiday, 1) == 1 ~ "PlusOneDay",
                                 dplyr::lag(holiday, 2) == 1 ~ "PlustTwoDays",
                                 dplyr::lag(holiday, 3) == 1 ~ "PlustThreeDays",
                                 dplyr::lead(holiday, 1) == 1 ~ "MinusOneDay",
                                 dplyr::lead(holiday, 2) == 1 ~ "MinusTwoDays",
                                 dplyr::lead(holiday, 3) == 1 ~ "MinusThreeDays"))%>%
    
   mutate(holidayLag = ifelse(is.na(holidayLag),0,holidayLag))

train the model:

reg1 <- lm(delay_minutes~Temperature+Precipitation+Wind_Speed+Visibility, data=trip.Train )
reg2 <- 
  lm(delay_minutes ~  line+holiday +  hour(interval60) + Temperature + Precipitation +Wind_Speed+Visibility+from, 
     data=trip.Train)
reg3 <- 
  lm(delay_minutes ~  line+holiday +  hour(interval60) + Temperature + Precipitation +Wind_Speed+Visibility+lagHour + lag2Hours +lag3Hours + lag12Hours + lag1day+holidayLag+leadHour+lead2Hours+lead3Hours+lead4Hours+lead12Hours+lead1day+from, 
     data=trip.Train)
